<section xml:id="MoreTrigonometricIdentities">
  <title>More Identities</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="FundamentalTrigonometricIdentities">Section</xref>,
      we saw the utility of identities in finding the values of the circular functions of a given angle as well as simplifying expressions involving the circular functions.
      In this section,
      we introduce several collections of identities which have uses in this course and beyond.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our first set of identities is the <sq>Even / Odd</sq> identities.
      We <em>observed</em> the even and odd properties of the circular functions graphically in <xref ref="GraphsofSineandCosine">Sections</xref>
      and <xref ref="GraphsofOtherCircularFunctions"></xref>.
      Here, we take the time to <em>prove</em>
      these properties from first principles.
      We state the theorem below for reference.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="evenodd">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <em>Even / Odd Identities:</em>
          For all applicable angles <m>\theta</m>,
              <idx><h>Even/Odd Identities</h></idx>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cos(-\theta) = \cos(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sec(-\theta) = \sec(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sin(-\theta) = -\sin(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\csc(-\theta) = -\csc(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tan(-\theta) = -\tan(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cot(-\theta) = -\cot(\theta)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We start by proving <m>\cos(-\theta) = \cos(\theta)</m> and <m>\sin(-\theta) = -\sin(\theta)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Consider an angle <m>\theta</m> plotted in standard position.
      Let <m>\theta_{0}</m> be the angle coterminal with <m>\theta</m> with <m>0 \leq \theta_{0} \lt 2\pi</m>.
      (We can construct the angle
      <m>\theta_{0}</m> by rotating counter-clockwise from the positive <m>x</m>-axis to the terminal side of <m>\theta</m> as pictured below.)
      Since <m>\theta</m> and <m>\theta_{0}</m> are coterminal,
      <m>\cos(\theta) = \cos(\theta_{0})</m> and <m>\sin(\theta) = \sin(\theta_{0})</m>.
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row>
        <cell>\begin{mfpic}[18]{-5}{5}{-4.5}{4.5}
          \axes
          \tlabel(4.75,-0.5){<m>x</m>}
          \tlabel(0.25,4.25){<m>y</m>}
          \tlabel(3.1,-0.75){<m>1</m>}
          \tlabel(0.25,3.1){<m>1</m>}
          \xmarks{-3 step 3 until 3}
          \ymarks{-3 step 3 until 3}
